This proposal adds a pattern! macro that can be used to specify a syntax tree pattern to search for. A simple pattern is shown below: pattern!{ my_pattern: Expr = Lit(Bool(false))
} This macro call defines a pattern named my_pattern that can be matched against an Expr syntax tree node. The actual pattern (Lit(Bool(false)) in this case) defines which syntax trees should match the pattern. This pattern matches expressions that are boolean literals with value false. The pattern can then be used to implement lints in the following way: ... impl EarlyLintPass for MyAwesomeLint { fn check_expr(&mut self, cx: &EarlyContext, expr: &syntax::ast::Expr) { if my_pattern(expr).is_some() { cx.span_lint( MY_AWESOME_LINT, expr.span, "This is a match for a simple pattern. Well done!", ); } }
} The pattern! macro call expands to a function my_pattern that expects a syntax tree expression as its argument and returns an Option that indicates whether the pattern matched. Note: The result type is explained in more detail in a later section . For now, it's enough to know that the result is Some if the pattern matched and None otherwise.

